	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=85616><span id=Guru>Lashara</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>189 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Grouping seems to be the meat and potatoes of EverQuest. And getting a good group is essential to your non-frustrated, fast leveling, enjoyment of Everquest. So how does a ranger make him/herself appealing to groups? We aren't great healers, or tanks, and we certainly can't mez the mob. And most people consider us the accessory class, once you have tank, healer and crowd control? So how does the group seeking ranger make sure that s/he gets picked to go into that fifth or sixth slot? Simple. You be the best group member you can be. And here's how.<br><br>1. Offer to pull. Outside of the monk, you are the best puller your group can have. Have Harmony and Snare up. Harmony first, then Snare. If you have SoW on, run backwards to your group firing arrows at the mob all the way. Stop. Flame lick. Stop. Attack. Wait til the mob is at 1/4 health. Rinse. Repeat. And here's a hint. Use 3rd person view from behind with the camera panned about halfway back. That way, while running backwards, you can still see where you're going and any incomming adds. You'll have eyes in the back of your head! (Literally).<br>2. Know your buffs. Druids get almost every buff you can offer. EXCEPT Feet Like Cat. This is an AGI boost that helps everyone get hit less. Make sure it's on everybody. Shamans get it too, but they may be reserving their gems for other spells. Offer it. Chances are, people will want it. If you don't have a druid, keep Skin and a Damage Shield on the tanking members. And make sure everyone has STR on (chanter STR is best, but shaman's and druids have their own strength spells so ask first to save mana - yours OR theirs).<br>3. Keep good tabs on your aggro. You want to be lower than the warriors on the aggro list, but above the rogues and the casters. And know how to get your aggro up quickly if the mob turns on someone you want him to leave alone. Flame lick and Snare are major aggro uppers. Taunt works well if paired with poor faction.<br>4. Know how to use /assist. You -should- be the main puller, but if for some reason you aren't, keep your target on whoever's pulling and macro a key for /assist. What this does: It makes you auto-attack whatever the puller is attacking when you press the button. This makes life much easier for enchanters who are trying their hardest to mez one of the mobs, and can't find one that someone in the group isn't beating on. (Very frustrating).<br>5. Appreciate your healers!!!! You'd be very suprised how often healers get left out of the loot cycle because they're so busy staring at their spell books and making sure they have enough mana to save your ass when things turn ugly. If you notice your healer seems to be getting the short end of the stick, send him/her a tell and offer to loot for him/her and split on a regular basis. They -do- appreciate it! Remember, without your healer, you are quite seriously DEAD MEAT.<br>6. Use root. Got an add? Use root. Caster getting beaten on? Use root. Someone's running around in circles and everyone else is trying to yank to mob off him or her because that member is dying? Use root. Need to make some aggro fast? Use root. Need a head start while you run for the hills? Use root. Looking to break the chanter's mez on that last mob? Use root. Any questions?<br>7. In group tell, when you join and when any other group member joins, state plainly to the group. &quot;If you are a caster and something aggros on you....scream!&quot; And when it happens.....cause it will... drop EVERYTHING and see number 6. Use root and aggro that mob!<br>8. Remember that your death proves nothing. If you are getting smashed around, back off and let someone else take a little bit of the heat. Even a caster if need be. If the whole group is going down, you should be among the first to die. However, in a fight that could go either way, you are more useful to your group alive, maybe healing and firing off arrows, than as a smear on the turf. Remember that.<br>9. Maintain a positive attitude and a good outlook, and be helpful whereever you can. If something went terribly wrong and you died, instead of freaking out and screaming at your group, offer to bring them food and water from the local city. The right outlook can make all the difference. <br><br>And finally, something I highly recommend to everyone.<br><br>Start at least one character of every class, and play that class til level 10. If you don't have time for every class, try a cleric, a bard and an enchanter as top priority. Understanding the role that a class plays in a group is crucial to appreciating them as a group member. Maybe it seems that the cleric is whining about not getting enough loot, but until you've played a cleric, you don't realize how often they get left out. Maybe you don't understand why the enchanter keeps screaming &quot;Use /assist you bunch of morons!&quot; Play one til level 8 and you will understand. Bards just seem to work differently than any other class (and I've played them all) and that's why I recommend playing them too.<br><br>Good grouping, rangers!</p>&nbsp;<br>Lashara Dyran<br>Keeper of the Wolves<br>Forest Stalker of Lanys T'Vyl<br></td></tr>
