	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=classes2.html?class=10&mid=100898828137722>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=classes2.html?class=10&mid=100898828137722>RE: How to be a good group member.</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes2.html?class=10&mid=100898828137722#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Fri, Dec 21st 9:31 PM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=85616><span id=Guru>Lashara</span></a><br><b><span id=Guru>Guru</span></b><br><span id=notbold>189 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.88]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Cannis;<br><br>Here's why I disagree. First of all I write all my posts for people 30 or under, because I've never experienced 30+ so I can't speak. These people do not have SoW (unless they get it from someone else, and even then some mobs run insanely fast) so kiting multiple adds sets you up for a world of hurt. I find it much more efficient to root an add before it hits the party. That way he can't hurt anybody, and if you do have a chanter, he'll have an easier time putting a mez/charm on the thing.<br><br>On the snare pulling and why I recommend it. Well, firstly, I do mostly short pulls from smaller camps. I don't pull for very long distances. So the time difference between snare vs. no snare is minimal. Secondly, I find if you time your pulls right, the group never notices how long you take to get a mob to them because you're already luring the next one in by the time they've finished the first. And lastly, I have never had a group complain about my pulling methods, so I don't think they -hate- it. The bonus of being able to run backwards and fire arrows at the mob during your pull is two-fold. One, you are doing damage. (Always good). Secondly, you are continually working your Archery skill, which can be a bugger to get up. Never had a problem with the tank not being able to taunt him off me. In fact, the only problem I -have- encountered with snare pulling is the increased risk of a wandering mob aggro-ing because of wandering into your slower moving prey.<br><br>Other than that, it's all been gravy.</p>&nbsp;<br>Lashara Dyran<br>Keeper of the Wolves<br>Forest Stalker of Lanys T'Vyl<br></td></tr>
